---
import DocsLayout from "../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

import { categories } from "../data/extensions";

const totalCount = categories.reduce((sum, category) => sum + category.extensions.length, 0);

const installTone = (install: string) => {
  if (install.startsWith("Default")) return "is-default";
  if (
    install.startsWith("Opt-in") ||
    install.startsWith("Library") ||
    install.startsWith("Not installable")
  )
    return "is-optin";
  return "is-conditional";
};
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Extension directory"
  eyebrow="Architecture"
  description="Every extension crate in the Roder workspace, organized by category, with what it provides and how it works."
  prev={{ href: "/docs/extensibility/", title: "Extension model" }}
  next={{ href: "/docs/event-bus/", title: "Events & replay" }}
>
  <p>
    This directory covers all {totalCount} <code>roder-ext-*</code> crates in the Roder workspace.
    Every extension implements the same contract: it declares a manifest
    (<code>id</code>, <code>version</code>, <code>provides</code>,
    <code>required_capabilities</code>) and installs typed services into the runtime registry.
    The runtime core never knows vendor specifics — it talks to the service interfaces.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Directory vs runtime.</strong> This page lists what exists in the source tree. The
    live runtime reports its installed set through the app-server <code>extensions/list</code>
    method — configuration, API keys, and distribution profiles decide which of these are
    actually active. Distribution profiles (<code>full</code>, <code>minimal</code>,
    <code>openai-only</code>, <code>anthropic-only</code>, <code>research-headless</code>) bundle
    different subsets.
  </div>

  <h2>Categories</h2>
  <ul class="columns-list">
    {categories.map((category) => (
      <li>
        <a href={`#${category.id}`}>{category.title}</a> ({category.extensions.length})
      </li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  {categories.map((category) => (
    <>
      <h2 id={category.id}>{category.title}</h2>
      <p>{category.intro}</p>
      <div class="ext-list">
        {category.extensions.map((ext) => (
          <article class="ext-card">
            <header class="ext-head">
              <code class="ext-name">{ext.crate}</code>
              <span class={`ext-install ${installTone(ext.install)}`}>{ext.install}</span>
            </header>
            <div class="ext-provides">
              {ext.provides.map((service) => (
                <code>{service}</code>
              ))}
            </div>
            <p class="ext-how">{ext.how}</p>
          </article>
        ))}
      </div>
    </>
  ))}

  <h2>How an extension plugs in</h2>
  <p>
    Regardless of category, every extension follows the same lifecycle:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Manifest.</strong> The crate implements <code>RoderExtension</code> and returns an
      <code>ExtensionManifest</code> describing itself and the sensitive capabilities it needs
      (network hosts, secrets, filesystem scopes, process spawning).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Install.</strong> The extension host calls <code>install</code>, and the extension
      registers its services — an inference engine, tool provider, store, runner, sink, or any
      combination — into the typed registry.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Gating.</strong> <code>build_default_registry</code> installs the stock set, but
      config and credentials gate conditional extensions: missing API keys suppress provider
      surfaces, <code>RODER_MEMORY_BACKEND</code> selects one memory store, web search and
      subagents appear only when enabled.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Use.</strong> The turn engine, tool policy, and task system resolve services from
      the registry at runtime — never from the crates directly — so any service can be replaced
      by an alternative implementation, including one running out-of-process via
      <code>roder-ext-process-host</code>.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For the service-type taxonomy and how to write your own extension, see the
    <a href="/docs/extensibility/">extension model</a> documentation.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>

<style>
  .ext-list {
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.85rem;
    margin: 1.4rem 0 2.2rem;
  }

  .ext-card {
    padding: 1rem 1.15rem 1.05rem;
    background: var(--bg-card, #fff);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 10px;
  }

  .ext-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    justify-content: space-between;
    gap: 0.8rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .ext-name {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--graphite);
    background: none;
    border: none;
    padding: 0;
  }

  .ext-install {
    font-family: var(--mono);
    font-size: 0.66rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    padding: 0.22rem 0.55rem;
    border-radius: 999px;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .ext-install.is-default {
    color: var(--teal-dark);
    background: rgba(10, 155, 141, 0.1);
  }

  .ext-install.is-conditional {
    color: var(--accent-strong);
    background: rgba(255, 77, 0, 0.09);
  }

  .ext-install.is-optin {
    color: rgba(23, 25, 29, 0.62);
    background: rgba(32, 41, 50, 0.07);
  }

  .ext-provides {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.32rem;
    margin-top: 0.55rem;
  }

  .ext-provides code {
    font-size: 0.74rem;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .ext-how {
    margin: 0.7rem 0 0;
    font-size: 0.94rem;
    line-height: 1.58;
    color: var(--fg-muted, rgba(23, 25, 29, 0.78));
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .ext-provides code {
      white-space: normal;
    }
  }
</style>
